    <h2 id="pros-cons">Pros and Cons</h2>
    <h3>Sony WH-1000XM5</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>✓ Best-in-class active noise cancellation for travel and offices</li>
      <li>✓ Excellent call quality with crisp voice pickup</li>
      <li>✓ Lightweight 250g design comfortable for long sessions</li>
      <li>✓ Smart features like adaptive sound control and speak-to-chat</li>
      <li>✓ LDAC support for high-res audio on Android</li>
      <li>✗ Battery life of 30 hours trails the Momentum 4 by half</li>
      <li>✗ No longer folds compactly, larger carrying case</li>
      <li>✗ Sound is tuned for mainstream appeal, less neutral than Sennheiser</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Sennheiser Momentum 4</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>✓ Class-leading 60-hour battery life with ANC on</li>
      <li>✓ Superior sound quality with warm, detailed signature</li>
      <li>✓ $100 cheaper than the Sony WH-1000XM5</li>
      <li>✓ Folds compactly into a smaller travel case</li>
      <li>✓ aptX Adaptive support for low-latency, high-quality streaming</li>
      <li>✗ Noise cancellation is good but a step behind Sony</li>
      <li>✗ Heavier at 293g, slightly less comfortable for very long wear</li>
      <li>✗ Call quality is competent but not as crisp as Sony's</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="performance">Performance</h2>
    <p>Active noise cancellation is where the Sony WH-1000XM5 establishes a clear lead. Sony's system uses eight microphones and two processors — one dedicated to noise cancellation and one for audio processing — to analyze and suppress ambient sound in real time. The result is the most effective consumer ANC available in 2026, handling low-frequency airplane engine drone, mid-range office chatter, and high-frequency HVAC hiss with remarkable consistency. The Momentum 4's adaptive ANC is good, and it does a credible job on commutes and in cafés, but it sits a clear step behind the Sony on the hardest noise sources like airplane cabins and busy trains. If noise cancellation is your top priority, the Sony is the category leader.</p>

    <p>Sound quality is where the Sennheiser Momentum 4 pulls ahead. Sennheiser's audiophile DNA shows in a tuning that is warmer, more detailed, and more naturally balanced than the Sony's more mainstream, bass-forward signature. The Momentum 4's 42mm drivers deliver a wider soundstage with better instrument separation, and vocals sit more forward in the mix in a way that flatters acoustic, jazz, and vocal-centric music. The Sony WH-1000XM5 is no slouch — its 30mm carbon fiber drivers are crisp and dynamic — but its default tuning emphasizes bass and treble in a way that is more immediately exciting but less accurate. With EQ adjustment in Sony's app, the gap narrows, but out of the box the Sennheiser is the better-sounding headphone for critical listening.</p>

    <p>Battery life is the Momentum 4's other decisive advantage. Its 60 hours of playback with ANC enabled is double the Sony's 30 hours, which means you can go a full week of heavy daily use between charges versus roughly three days on the Sony. Both support quick charging, but the Sennheiser's endurance is genuinely liberating for travel — a single charge can cover a long-haul flight and a week of commuting with capacity to spare. On comfort, the lighter Sony (250g vs 293g) feels less fatiguing across marathon listening sessions, though both have plush earcups and well-padded headbands. Call quality favors the Sony, whose microphone array delivers clearer, more natural voice pickup on calls and video meetings than the Sennheiser's competent but slightly muddier mic.</p>

    <h2 id="price">Price</h2>
    <p>The Sennheiser Momentum 4 launched at $349 and now regularly sells for $299, making it $100 cheaper than the Sony WH-1000XM5's $399 price. That price gap is meaningful: for the cost of the Sony, you could buy the Momentum 4 and still have $100 left over, or you could view it as paying a $100 premium for the Sony's superior noise cancellation and call quality.</p>

    <p>Both headphones represent good value relative to their strengths. The Sony's $399 buys the best noise cancellation and call quality in the consumer category, justifying the premium for frequent travelers and anyone who takes a lot of calls from their headphones. The Sennheiser's $299 buys class-leading battery life and superior sound quality, making it the better value for music-focused listeners who do not need top-tier ANC. When both go on sale — and both discount regularly during major shopping events — the Momentum 4 often drops below $250, which makes it an exceptional deal, while the Sony rarely falls far below $329. For budget-conscious buyers who value sound and battery over absolute noise cancellation, the Momentum 4 is the stronger value proposition.</p>

    <h2 id="who-wins">Who Wins</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>For noise cancellation and travel:</strong> Sony WH-1000XM5 wins because its eight-microphone, dual-processor system is the best consumer ANC available, silencing airplanes, trains, and offices more effectively than any competitor.</li>
      <li><strong>For sound quality:</strong> Sennheiser Momentum 4 wins because its 42mm drivers and warmer, more detailed tuning deliver a more natural, audiophile-pleasing sound than the Sony's bass-forward signature.</li>
      <li><strong>For battery life:</strong> Sennheiser Momentum 4 wins decisively with 60 hours of playback with ANC on, double the Sony's 30 hours.</li>
      <li><strong>For calls and video meetings:</strong> Sony WH-1000XM5 wins because its microphone array produces clearer, more natural voice pickup for calls and remote work.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="recommendation">Final Recommendation</h2>
    <p>If you prioritize noise cancellation, call quality, and smart features, the Sony WH-1000XM5 is the best premium wireless headphone you can buy in 2026. Its adaptive ANC silences the world more effectively than anything else on the market, its lightweight design is comfortable for all-day wear, and its microphone system makes it a genuine work-from-home tool as well as a travel essential. At $399 it is not cheap, but for frequent flyers, commuters, and remote workers who live in their headphones, the premium is well justified.</p>

    <p>If you prioritize sound quality and battery life above all, the Sennheiser Momentum 4 is the better choice. Its 60-hour battery, warmer and more detailed sound, and $299 price make it the value pick of the premium category, and for music-focused listeners who do not need class-leading ANC, it is arguably the more satisfying headphone to listen to. The fact that it folds more compactly and costs $100 less only strengthens the case.</p>

    <p>The simplest way to decide: choose the Sony WH-1000XM5 if noise cancellation and calls matter most; choose the Sennheiser Momentum 4 if sound quality and battery life matter most. Both are excellent flagship headphones, and neither will leave you disappointed — they simply optimize for different priorities.</p>
